    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="678"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d678">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">196.6/1152</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Swedish Legation</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p>A bill has been introduced by Senator <persName>LaFollette</persName> numbered S.
                    1558 and entitled: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“A Bill to amend certain laws relating to American Seamen, and for other
                                purposes”.<note n="5" xml:id="d678fn5">Introduced December 14, 1931;
                                see <hi rend="italic">Congressional Record</hi>, vol. 75, pt. 1, p.
                                440.</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Reference is made to the memorandum of this Legation dated January 14, 1932,
                    concerning the bill 1559, introduced by Senator <persName>LaFollette</persName>.
                    It would seem that the same arguments set forth in that memorandum can be
                    applied in opposition to the passage of the above mentioned bill No. 1558.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-04">April 4,
                            1932</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
